Global Cropland Expansion and Soils at Risk

A Terra Tutorial

Mandy Liesch

Purpose

Scientific Purpose: There are several causes of anthropogenic climate changes. Land use change, especially deforestation and cropland expansion, creates several different emissions that contribute to extra carbon dioxide in the atmosphere. The scientific objective of this vignette is to visualize the cropland gains by country, as well as the soil carbon levels of these countries. The second portion of the Vignette focuses only on the pixels that are experiencing greater than 10% conversion into croplands, and their soil carbon content. This second objective identifies which areas are experiencing high levels of conversion, with high carbon. These ares are considered high risk areas.

Coding Purpose: The purpose of this vignette is exploring the functionality of the Terra package for manipulating rasters, masking, and clipping. Terra is an evolution to the raster package, and stores information, especially large raster files, into a computer in a way that makes them faster and easier to process. Once these initial processing steps are done, the exact_extract and raster package to extract the zonal statistics into an attribute table. The terra package has an extract option; however, it is much slower when processing large, and more complex datasets (though much faster with smaller ones). Then, these spatVectors will be merged with the coulumns created from the raster values, and visualized with bivariate cholopleth maps in ggplot.

A Note on file size:

A lot of these files, especially the temporary ones are quite large in RAM. There are several ways to deal with this, including the use of terraOptions. To get around this, I used an external hard drive (F:/) to change where the temporary Spatraster files are stored using this command. This function eliminated the failures caused by a full temp drive.

terraOptions(tempDir="F:/temp")

R Packages

Spatial Processing Packages

terra: This package is the new gold standard in geospatial processing. It is faster than the raster and sf package, and was designed specifically for satellite image processing and other large raster projects. There is an extensive geospatial tutorial with many examples.

geodata: A package for the downloading geographic data, including administrative boundaries at several levels.

exactextractr: This package allows fast extraction of raster data to shapefiles.

The Geospatial Data Abstraction Library (GDAL), is an open source software for reading and writing raster and vector geospatial data formats. It is integrated in many different softwares, and supports many different file types. There are two different gdal packages.

rgdal: This is the R software integration of the Geospatial Data Abstraction Library (GDAL). Please note that rgdal will be retired by the end of 2023, plan transition to sf/stars/terra functions using GDAL and PROJ at your earliest convenience.

gdalUtils: This is the developmental raster tool behind the Geospatial Data Abstraction Library (GDAL).

sf: a standardized way to encode spatial vector data that binds to GDAL for reading and writing data.

Visualization Packages

ggplot2: A part of the R tidyverse, and one of the most versatile graphics package, with builds and extensions.

Ridge plots are a chart that is used to visualize distributions of several groups of a category, in this case, the distributions are covered by region/continent.

ggridges:

A Bivariate Chloropleth Maps are a type of thematic visualization that present two or more different numeric values on a single map. The chloropleth map is the most standard of these, with each value (in this case, country), getting classified into a two dimensional matrix (with value 1 determined by one variable, and value 2 determined by the second variable). The legend is divided into smaller boxes where each box represents a unique relationship of the variables (category 1-1, up to category 3-3). To run this analysis, these packages are required:

biscale: This method is used with ggplot to create the matrix necessary to make bivariate choloropleth maps.

cowplot: This package is a generic graphics package that provides help with creating publication-quality figures with ggplot. For the bivariate chloropleth maps, it helps us add the legend and dynamic positioning. There are several other functions it can do.

Data Manipulation Packages

Soil Grids: Total Soil Carbon Stocks 0-30 cm

SoilGrids is a system for global digital soil mapping that makes use of global soil profile information and covariate data to model the spatial distribution of soil properties across the globe. SoilGrids is a collections of soil property maps for the world produced using machine learning at 250 m resolution. The Soil Grids 2.0 FAQs details the file structure and downloads for both the soil grids data for soil carbon, as well as the uncertainty.

This code process takes you through how to grab the WebDAV protocol modelled off of the SoilGrids Notebook, using the GDAL functionality in R.

library(rgdal)
library(gdalUtils)

link="/vsicurl/https://files.isric.org/soilgrids/latest/data/ocs/ocs_0-30cm_Q0.5.vrt"

gdal_translate(link,
    "soilC_Rast.tif",
    co=c("TILED=YES","COMPRESS=DEFLATE","BIGTIFF=YES"),
    verbose=TRUE)
scStock<-rast("soilC_Rast.tif")

plot(scStock)

project(scStock, w, filename="Reproj_SoilC.tif")
scStock<-rast("Reproj_SoilC.tif")

plot(scStock)
plot(w, bg="transparent", add=TRUE)

Cropland Extent Changes

The dataset represents a globally consistent cropland extent time-series at 30-m spatial resolution. Cropland defined as land used for annual and perennial herbaceous crops for human consumption, forage (including hay), and biofuel. It is on the Global Land Analysis and Discovery, on a project through the University of Maryland.

The chosen rasters downloaded are the Cropland Gain (Global_cropland_3km_netgain.tif).

The net cropland extent change from 2003 to 2019 is shown as the Pixel value: 0-100, percent of cropland dynamic (loss or gain) per pixel.

cropGain<-rast("Global_cropland_3km_netgain.tif")


project(cropGain, scStock, filename="Reproj_cropGain.tif")
gains<-rast("Reproj_cropGain.tif")

plot(gains)
plot(w, bg="transparent", add=TRUE)

  geom_sf(data = shapes, mapping = aes(fill = bi_class), color = "white", size = 0.1, show.legend = FALSE) +
  bi_scale_fill(pal = "DkBlue", dim = 3) +
  labs(
    title = "Cropland Gains and 30 cm Carbon Stocks",
  ) +
  bi_theme()

                    dim = 3,
                    xlab = "Cropland Gain",
                    ylab = "Carbon Stocks",
                    size = 12)

finalPlot <- ggdraw() +
  draw_plot(map, 0, 0, 1, 1) +
  draw_plot(legend, 0, 0.2, 0.2, 0.2)

Detailed Analysis

target<-gains>=10


targMask<-classify(
#define the raster you are clipping
target,
#define the reclassification values (id is 0= not in the 10% or more)
cbind(id=c(0, 1),
#these are the raster values, with an id of 0 returning as an NA, otherwise it is 1.
v=c(NA, 1)),
filename='targMask.tif')
targetMask<-rast("targMask.tif")
highCrop<-mask(
#the first raster is the full raster we are cutting (the soil carbon stocks)
scStock,
#the second raster is the mask we created in the previous step
targetMask,
#If TRUE, areas on mask that are _not_ the maskvalue are masked, since we classified them as NA, this can be set to false
inverse=FALSE,
#The value that cells of x should become if they are not covered by mask, set to NA here.
updatevalue=NA,
#new creation of a .tif file, with the cut values of soil carbon remaining.
filename="highCrop_SOC_Stocks.tif")
highCropCh<-rast("highCrop_SOC_Stocks.tif")

plot(highCropCh)
plot(w, bg="transparent", add=TRUE)

shapes$hCCount<-exact_extract(highCropCh, shapes, 'count')
